1 (11)[(10)] (a) The cost of extraordinary medical expenses shall be allocated between
2 the parties in proportion to their combined monthly adjusted parental gross
3 incomes.
4 (b) 1. "Extraordinary medical expenses" means uninsured expenses in excess
5 of two hundred fifty dollars ($250) for the child or children subject to
6 the order per calendar year.
7 2. "Extraordinary medical expenses" includes but is not limited to the costs
8 that are reasonably necessary for:
9 a. Medical, surgical, dental, orthodontal, optometric, nursing, and
10 hospital services;[ for]
11 b. Professional counseling or psychiatric therapy for diagnosed
12 medical disorders; and[ for]
13 c. Drugs and medical supplies, appliances, laboratory, diagnostic,
14 and therapeutic services.
15 (12)[(11)] The court order shall include the Social Security numbers, provided in
16 accordance with KRS 403.135, of all parties subject to a support order.
17 (13)[(12)] In any case administered by the Cabinet for Health and Family Services, if the
18 parent ordered to provide health care coverage is enrolled through an insurer but
19 fails to enroll the child under family coverage, the other parent or the Cabinet for
20 Health and Family Services may, upon application, enroll the child.
21 (14)[(13)] In any case administered by the cabinet, information received or transmitted
22 shall not be published or be open for public inspection, including reasonable
23 evidence of domestic violence or child abuse if the disclosure of the information
24 could be harmful to the custodial parent or the child of the parent. Necessary
25 information and records may be furnished as specified by KRS 205.175.
26 (15)[(14)] In the case in which a parent is obligated to provide health care coverage, and
27 changes employment, and the new employer provides health care coverage, the
